<div class="dablink">Not to be confused with <a href="Burro_Banton" title="Burro Banton">Burro Banton</a>.</div>
<p><b>Buju Banton</b> (born <b>Mark Anthony Myrie</b> 15 July 1973)<sup id="cite_ref-Larkin_1-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Larkin-1"><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> is a <a href="Jamaica" title="Jamaica">Jamaican</a> <a href="Dancehall" title="Dancehall">dancehall</a>, <a href="Ragga" title="Ragga">ragga</a>, and <a href="Reggae" title="Reggae">reggae</a> <a href="Musician" title="Musician">musician</a>. Banton has recorded <a href="Pop_music" title="Pop music">pop</a> and <a href="Dance_music" title="Dance music">dance</a> songs, as well as songs dealing with <a href="Sociopolitical" title="Sociopolitical" class="mw-redirect">sociopolitical</a> topics.</p>
<p>He released early dancehall singles in 1991, but came to prominence in 1992 with two albums, including <i>Mr. Mention</i>, which became the best-selling album in Jamaican history upon its release. Banton signed with major label <a href="Mercury_Records" title="Mercury Records">Mercury Records</a> and released <i>Voice of Jamaica</i> the following year. By the mid-1990s, Banton had converted to the <a href="Rastafari" title="Rastafari" class="mw-redirect">Rastafari</a> faith, and his music undertook a more spiritual tone. His 2010 album <i>Before the Dawn</i> was the winner for Best Reggae Album at the 53rd annual Grammy Awards.</p>
<p>Banton gained international notoriety early on in his career for the anti-gay track "Boom Bye Bye", as well as for his 2009 arrest and conviction in the United States on drug conspiracy and firearms charges, for which he is currently serving a ten-year federal prison sentence. He is scheduled to be released January 2019.</p>
